And so when I was at college, I studied microeconomics and macroeconomics, and I took an interest in commodity markets, particularly wool and wheat markets. And the more I looked into it, the more I thought becoming a commodity analyst would be an interesting job. I really wasn't aware that trade has existed. So they both felt it would be a better idea for me to go somewhere where nobody spoke any English at all in order to learn Japanese properly. And he suggested to me the idea of going and staying in this temple. And I went to the temple in Yamanashi Prefecture and guaranteed there was not a person who spoke English around there. And I thought, yeah, I'll give it a go. So within a week of arriving in Tokyo, I was in this 500 year old Zen temple with a small number of monks. I spoke basically one semester's worth of Japanese from college. But I had no idea what was the problem. But I spent a year there really kind of learning to speak Japanese, working on various projects around the temple itself. I did Zazen every day. And over time, my Japanese became passable.
